# Lumina Scope Patterns

Scopes in Lumina control **which records** a user can see. They filter query results based on the authenticated user's role within the current organization. Scopes are different from Policies: policies decide **can they do it**, scopes decide **what they can see**.

## Implementing a Scope

Scopes must implement Laravel's `Scope` interface:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models\Scopes;

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Builder;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Scope;

class ArticleScope implements Scope
{
    public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
    {
        $user = auth()->user();

        // Handle unauthenticated users gracefully
        if (!$user) {
            $builder->whereRaw('1 = 0'); // Return no results
            return;
        }

        $roles = $user->rolesInOrganization();

        // Admins see all records in the organization (no additional filtering)
        if ($roles->contains('slug', 'admin')) {
            return;
        }

        // Editors see published articles and their own drafts
        if ($roles->contains('slug', 'editor')) {
            $builder->where(function ($query) use ($user) {
                $query->where('status', 'published')
                      ->orWhere('author_id', $user->id);
            });
            return;
        }

        // Default: only see published articles
        $builder->where('status', 'published');
    }
}
```

## Registering a Scope on the Model

Register the scope in the model's `booted()` method:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models;

use App\Models\Scopes\ArticleScope;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Factories\HasFactory;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\SoftDeletes;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HasValidation;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HidableColumns;

class Article extends \Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model
{
    use HasFactory;
    use SoftDeletes;
    use HasValidation;
    use HidableColumns;

    protected static function booted(): void
    {
        static::addGlobalScope(new ArticleScope());
    }
}
```

## Handling Unauthenticated Users

Always handle the case where no user is authenticated. Never throw exceptions -- return an empty result set instead:

```php
public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
{
    $user = auth()->user();

    if (!$user) {
        // Gracefully return no results for unauthenticated users
        $builder->whereRaw('1 = 0');
        return;
    }

    // ... role-based filtering
}
```

## Preventing Infinite Recursion with User Model

If you create a scope for the `User` model, be careful not to trigger recursive queries. Avoid calling relationships on the user that would re-query the User model with the same scope:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models\Scopes;

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Builder;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Scope;

class UserScope implements Scope
{
    public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
    {
        $user = auth()->user();

        if (!$user) {
            $builder->whereRaw('1 = 0');
            return;
        }

        $roles = $user->rolesInOrganization();

        // Admins see all users in the organization
        if ($roles->contains('slug', 'admin')) {
            return;
        }

        // Non-admins only see active users
        // DO NOT load User relationships here that would re-trigger this scope
        $builder->where('is_active', true);
    }
}
```

## HasAutoScope Trait

As an alternative to manual registration, use the `HasAutoScope` trait. It automatically discovers and applies a scope class following the naming convention `App\Models\Scopes\{ModelName}Scope`:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models;

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Factories\HasFactory;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\SoftDeletes;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HasValidation;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HidableColumns;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HasAutoScope;

class Article extends \Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model
{
    use HasFactory;
    use SoftDeletes;
    use HasValidation;
    use HidableColumns;
    use HasAutoScope;

    // No need to override booted() -- HasAutoScope automatically
    // looks for App\Models\Scopes\ArticleScope and applies it.
}
```

The convention is:
- Model: `App\Models\Article`
- Scope: `App\Models\Scopes\ArticleScope`

## Complete Example

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models\Scopes;

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Builder;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Scope;

class ProjectScope implements Scope
{
    public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
    {
        $user = auth()->user();

        if (!$user) {
            $builder->whereRaw('1 = 0');
            return;
        }

        $roles = $user->rolesInOrganization();

        // Admins: see all projects
        if ($roles->contains('slug', 'admin')) {
            return;
        }

        // Managers: see all active projects and their own archived ones
        if ($roles->contains('slug', 'manager')) {
            $builder->where(function ($query) use ($user) {
                $query->where('status', '!=', 'archived')
                      ->orWhere('owner_id', $user->id);
            });
            return;
        }

        // Members: only see projects they are assigned to
        $builder->whereHas('members', function ($query) use ($user) {
            $query->where('user_id', $user->id);
        });
    }
}
```

## DON'Ts

- **DO NOT** perform action authorization in scopes. Scopes filter data visibility; policies handle action authorization (create, update, delete).

```php
// BAD: Authorization logic in scope
public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
{
    if (!auth()->user()->can('viewAny', Article::class)) {
        $builder->whereRaw('1 = 0'); // Wrong! This is policy logic.
    }
}
```

- **DO NOT** modify data in scopes. Scopes should only add query constraints, never create, update, or delete records.

```php
// BAD: Data modification in scope
public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
{
    auth()->user()->update(['last_query_at' => now()]); // Wrong! No side effects.
    $builder->where('status', 'active');
}
```

- **DO NOT** throw exceptions for unauthenticated users. Return an empty result set instead.

```php
// BAD: Throwing exception
public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
{
    $user = auth()->user();
    if (!$user) {
        throw new \Exception('User must be authenticated'); // Wrong!
    }
}

// GOOD: Graceful handling
public function apply(Builder $builder, Model $model): void
{
    $user = auth()->user();
    if (!$user) {
        $builder->whereRaw('1 = 0'); // Return no results
        return;
    }
}
```
